{"key":"processedPost-18572266","value":{"id":18572266,"first":18563973,"last":18572851,"when":1374100832,"utime":"07/18/13 01:40 AM","content":"If the yield is equal from the top or sides, what does it matter?&nbsp; The fact is, the mycelium fruits where it wants to, not where it's best for us.&nbsp; There's usually as much or nearly as much surface area around the edges as there is on the whole top, depending on depth of substrate.&nbsp; <br /><br />As an added benefit, once the substrate shrinks due to <i>being consumed by mycelium</i>, you can pour water around the edges to rehydrate it easily.&nbsp; Some of the biggest monster mushrooms posted here grew from the edges of the substrate, not the top.&nbsp; <br /><br />It's also a function of strain sometimes in that despite our best efforts at surface moisture management, often they just fruit around the edges anyway. <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/shrug.gif\" alt=\":shrug:\" title=\":shrug:\"/><br />RR","title":"Re: Serious problem","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}